  "response": "The main difference between O- and O+ blood types is the presence or absence of the Rh factor:\n\nO- (O negative):\n- Does not have the Rh factor\n- Universal donor blood type\n- Can donate to all blood types\n- Only 7% of people have this type\n- Rh negative individuals can only receive Rh negative blood\n\nO+ (O positive):\n- Has the Rh factor\n- Can donate to O+ and O- blood types\n- Most common blood type (about 38-40% of people)\n- Rh positive individuals can receive both Rh positive and Rh negative blood\n\nThe key distinction is the \"+\" or \"-\" indicating the presence or absence of the Rh factor on red blood cells.",
